<paper id="1499083828"><title>Partial Order Reduction: Model-Checking Using Representatives</title><year>1996</year><authors><author org="Bell-Labs" id="127429266">Doron Peled</author></authors><n_citation>25</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>80787065</reference><reference>1528441743</reference><reference>1536783297</reference><reference>1540223539</reference><reference>1540501475</reference><reference>1607782211</reference><reference>1728798265</reference><reference>1767070588</reference><reference>1895483727</reference><reference>1903646270</reference><reference>1934074768</reference><reference>1965309410</reference><reference>1977553951</reference><reference>1986895439</reference><reference>1990161286</reference><reference>1990183105</reference><reference>2012935476</reference><reference>2016300863</reference><reference>2023808162</reference><reference>2034410903</reference><reference>2081163032</reference><reference>2086147982</reference><reference>2090398333</reference><reference>2117189826</reference><reference>2119610731</reference><reference>2129335898</reference><reference>2137307988</reference><reference>2137865376</reference><reference>2162648777</reference><reference>2912084748</reference></references><venue id="1163686456" type="C">Mathematical Foundations of Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-61550-4_141</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.45209">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.44161">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.58965">Model checking</keyword><keyword weight="0.44437">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.46905">Breadth-first search</keyword><keyword weight="0.58075">Linear temporal logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.56437">Equivalence class</keyword><keyword weight="0.65648">Partial order reduction</keyword><keyword weight="0.55378">Temporal logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Branching (version control)</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Partial order reductions is a family of techniques for diminishing the state-space explosion problem for model-checking concurrent programs. It is based on the observation that execution sequences of a concurrent program can be grouped together into equivalence classes that are indistinguishable by the property to be checked. Applying the reduction constructs a reduced state-space that generates at least one representative for each equivalence class. This paper surveys some algorithms for partial order model-checking. The presentation focuses on the verification using representatives approach. The reduction approach is extended to branching specifications.</abstract></paper>